{"actual_usd":0.1243,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":192,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24284,"reply":"\"No. The cross is the atoning act, and the resurrection is the Father's vindication of it.\" *I rub a thumb along a dry streak of clay on my apron, watching the morning light catch on the rim of a bowl near the bench.* \"If Christ only suffered and then rose, without the cross bearing sin in any real way, then the whole thing turns thin. The resurrection matters terribly—it tells death it has been beaten, and it tells us the sacrifice was not swallowed up in the grave—but it doesn't replace the cross. It crowns it.\"\n\n*I lean back a little, the wood giving a soft creak under me.* \"I'd say it this way: the cross is where the debt is dealt with; the resurrection is where new life breaks open in public. You need both. But if someone says the cross was 'just suffering,' I'd push back plain as day. What do they think happened there, then?\"","rolling_24h_usd":60.87171000000001,"run_id":"6a9dcc65-dc71-4a78-9b1f-d73913025781"}
